				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">This answer assumes that you are unwilling to infringe any copyright. (I imagine some infringements are likely to be overlooked, but that's for someone else to answer.)<br /><br />If a homebrew is released as <a href="https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/free-sw.en.html" class="postlink">free software</a>, you are free to make and sell a repro. If a homebrew is not free software but is otherwise licensed to you for commercial use, you are likewise free to make and sell a repro. So I'd recommend reproducing original homebrew games, not translations or other mods of well-known proprietary games that were either released commercially or made with the intent of a commercial release, unless you can negotiate a license with the game's copyright owner. If you're also doing NES, I've started a topic listing <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=116794#p116794" class="postlink">games that are OK to reproduce</a>.</div>

