			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If a homebrew is not free software but is licensed for commercial use, you are likewise free to make and sell a repro.</div><br />This is a very strange statement.<br /><br />Homebrews are copyright in the same way that any other game is. Their owner can place them in the public domain, or otherwise license them for free use, in which case it is legal to do this stuff, but &quot;licened for commercial use&quot; doesn't sound like it describes this adequately.<br /><br />e.g. Super Mario Bros is certainly &quot;licensed for commercial use&quot;, but it's not licensed to you or me for commercial use.<br /><br />It may sound like I'm being tautological here, but I just want to make it crystal clear that homebrew is <em>not</em> fair game for repros unless the author explicitly says so (often in the form of a standard license like &quot;creative commons&quot;). Homebrew is no different than other games in this respect. For anything that isn't explicitly under a free use license, you must contact the owner and negotiate with them.<br /><br />Also, just because something is available for free doesn't mean it's licensed for you to make copies of it, either. I could put up a ROM for free download, but that doesn't give anybody else the right to rehost it, make copies of it, etc. unless I actually say so. Jordan Mechner can release the <a href="https://github.com/jmechner/Prince-of-Persia-Apple-II" class="postlink">source code to Prince of Persia</a> freely, but this doesn't give anyone a license to make and sell copies of that game, nor does the free release of the source code give anyone the right to copy substantial material from it to reuse for their own purposes.<br /><br />All 5 examples in your original post are clearly copyright violations, by the way. Changing part of a ROM doesn't negate copyright on everything left unchanged. You could replace all the graphics and all the levels in a game, but the remaining code in the game would still be a copyright violation. Changing the region doesn't negate it either, these things are protected by international copyright treaties.</div>

					
