					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">NYMike wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Makes me wonder though how so many people are reproducing all over (from Canada to China to US) and I have not heard of Nintendo stomping down on them.</div><br />There's a lot of them, and each infringement of copyright is on a relatively small scale. The technically could go after them, but it's a lot of work for little gain. Usually lawsuits against such a small thing like that seem like they're pursued to make an example to the rest, in hope that fear will deter them.<br /><br />China itself is a place where I understand that copyright law is not very well enforced. Similarly there are a lot of loopholes in internet piracy involving hosting copyrighted material in particular countries to avoid prosecution. Illegal distribution of ROM files on the internet is probably 100,000x more prevalent than illegal repros. (That might be a low estimate, but in terms of what should be on their radar, repros are fairly low.)<br /><br />So, all in all, it seems like most repro sellers are at relatively low risk for being sued for copyright infringement, but the risk is there.<br /><br />Now, I don't know who is liable for copyright infringement if, say, someone were to give you a ROM file, and you just create a cartridge for them. You might draft a standard form, wherein they state that they own the rights to use the ROM they're giving you and are responsible for any liability due to misrepresentation of that. I've seen agreements like this for similar service. Don't ask me how well they'd hold up in court (I'm sure there's lots of cases where it wouldn't), but it does seem like a reasonable precaution. The law is still being broken, but at least it might shift the burden of this to the buyer, somewhat?</div>

