				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Jan 22, 2012 12:03 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 6592<br /><b>Location:</b> Canada
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">darryl.revok wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Does anyone know if it's legal to make a physical copy of a game that you own, for backup?<br /><br />Like, you can have a ROM if you own the game. Wouldn't making a backup cart be about the same as making a copy of a VHS tape?</div><br />I think backups for personal use (i.e. no transfer of ownership) are usually considered exempt from copyright violation. However, if you had to defeat some kind of security measures to do it, you may be violating the Digtial Millenium Copyright Act? i.e. the copying itself isn't what's illegal in this case, just the tampering with copy-protection devices. There are some exemptions to the DMCA as well, but it's very complicated/nebulous. I don't really understand it very well myself, so don't take my word for any of this.<br /><br />In practice, you're <em>extremely unlikely</em> to be sued for privately making copies for yourself, even if you're technically violating the DMCA to do it.<br /><br />You're also pretty unlikely to be sued for making copies of stuff and giving it to your friends, or in large part even for selling it. It's against the law, but it's not easy to enforce. Piracy is rampant.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

